{{wikipedia}}
==English==

===Etymology===
Middle English ''cunte'' from Old English ''*cunte'' (probably present though not attested), from West Germanic ''*kunte'', from Germanic ''*kunton''. Cognate with Frisian [[kunte]], dialectal Swedish [[kunta]], dialectal Danish [[kunte]], Dutch [[kont]] ‘arse’. A relationship to Latin [[cunnus]] has not been conclusively shown.

===Pronunciation===
*{{AHD|kŭnt}}, {{IPA|/kʌnt/}}, {{SAMPA|/kVnt/}}
* Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-ʌnt|-ʌnt]]

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# (''vulgar slang'') the female [[genitalia]], especially the [[vulva]].
#: 
# (''vulgar slang'') An extremely unpleasant or objectionable person (in US, especially a woman).
#: ''You utter '''cunt'''.''
# (''vulgar slang'') A [[objectionable]] object or item
#: ''Fix the car? I'll sort the '''cunt''' out at the weekend.''
# (''vulgar slang'') An [[unpleasant]] or [[difficult]] experience or incident
#: ''I had a'' '''''cunt''''' ''of a day.'' ''It was a'' '''''cunt''''' ''of an experience getting through it.''
# (''vulgar slang, countable and uncountable'') a [[woman]] or [[women]] as a source of [[sex]]
#: ''I'm going to hit the bars and see if I can get me some '''cunt'''.''
# (''vulgar slang'') A man, used non-pejoratively.
#: ''I liked that guy he was a good '''cunt'''.''

====Usage notes====
Definitions 3, 4, and 6 may not be in common usage in North America.

